+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Qa1v7CEFDfJyo1LA3hWFU2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Inversion Step 3 — Exploring the Negation Space:**\n\nThe inverted approach reveals several powerful design choices:\n\n1. **Eager evaluation on `set()`**: When a cell is set, immediately compute its value AND propagate to all dependents. `get()` becomes O(1) — just a map lookup. This is how real spreadsheets work.\n\n2. **Explicit dependency graph**: Maintain `dependsOn` (what a cell references) and `dependedOnBy` (reverse — who depends on this cell). When a cell changes, topologically sort its dependents and recompute in order. Only affected cells are touched.\n\n3. **Recursive descent parser**: A proper parser with operator precedence handles `=A1+B1*2` correctly (multiplication before addition) without hacky regex.\n\n4. **Cycle detection at set-time**: Before committing a formula, check if the new dependencies would create a cycle in the graph. If so, throw an error and leave the cell unchanged. This prevents the cell from ever entering an invalid state.\n\n5. **Topological sort for recomputation order**: When propagating changes, compute dependents in topological order so each cell is evaluated after all its dependencies."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":276,"cache_read_input_tokens":19451,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":276},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ccc0ed95-1561-4ee8-85ed-9b8b5d45960c","uuid":"e0e730e0-10b5-445e-9327-ffed16f88c5b"}
